WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.240 --> 00:00:03.405
MIRA GRANT: So hello.

00:00:03.405 --> 00:00:06.550
I'm Mira Grant.

00:00:06.550 --> 00:00:08.210
That's Mira Grant's
mom in the back,

00:00:08.210 --> 00:00:10.590
pretending she's not here
with all of us weirdos.

00:00:10.590 --> 00:00:11.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:14.390
And I am here today
because I was asked to be,

00:00:14.390 --> 00:00:17.980
which is a great reason to
be at the Google campus.

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:20.590
So I'm going to be
reading to you today

00:00:20.590 --> 00:00:24.860
from "When Will You Rise," which
is a short hardcover I put out

00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:26.130
a couple years ago.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:28.260
Because its got some pieces
in it that are actually

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:32.066
a good length to read and don't
leave you going wait, what?

00:00:32.066 --> 00:00:33.690
The last timed reading
I did, I stopped

00:00:33.690 --> 00:00:35.500
in the middle of a word.

00:00:35.500 --> 00:00:36.965
To be fair, it was
a very long word

00:00:36.965 --> 00:00:38.610
that I didn't want
to pronounce anyway.

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:40.860
But it was still
sort of a jarring

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:42.187
for the people involved.

00:00:42.187 --> 00:00:43.770
After the reading,
we're going to have

00:00:43.770 --> 00:00:46.070
a brief Q&amp;A. I know some
of you all have books.

00:00:46.070 --> 00:00:46.730
I have a pen.

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:49.010
I am happy to scribble
on your books.

00:00:49.010 --> 00:00:51.300
I'm actually happy to scribble
on just about anything.

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:54.480
If you really work the Q&amp;A, we
might engage the whiteboard.

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:57.330
So think of questions
that will require

00:00:57.330 --> 00:00:59.840
diagramming sentences
or explaining

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:02.950
how the R0 works and
we will go there.

00:01:02.950 --> 00:01:08.960
So this is "Apocalypse
Scenario, #683, The Box."

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:10.700
"Andy, where's the beer?"

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:11.940
"Look in the crisper."

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:14.590
Ryan paused before
asking the obvious.

00:01:14.590 --> 00:01:16.660
"Why is the beer
in the crisper?"

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:19.450
"Because grain's a vegetable."
said Elsa, sensibly enough,

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:22.470
as she dumps tortilla chips
into a yellow plastic bowl.

00:01:22.470 --> 00:01:24.634
"That means beer
is good for you."

00:01:24.634 --> 00:01:26.300
"I don't even know
what to say to that,"

00:01:26.300 --> 00:01:28.950
said Ryan, before digging a beer
out from under a wilted head

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:30.010
of lettuce.

00:01:30.010 --> 00:01:31.310
"Is Mike coming?"

00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:33.090
"Mike's coming, Cole isn't."

00:01:33.090 --> 00:01:34.950
Andy picked up the
tray of sandwiches,

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:36.480
pausing to kiss
Elsa on the cheek

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:38.220
before exiting the kitchen.

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:40.290
The tray of sandwiches
was placed ceremonious

00:01:40.290 --> 00:01:43.180
on the dining room table,
next to a veggie platter,

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:46.890
a bowl of salsa, and a second
bowl filled with peanut M&amp;Ms.

00:01:46.890 --> 00:01:49.290
He glanced back, as Ryan
followed him to the table,

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.800
adding, "Before you
ask," Sandi's coming.

00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:54.410
"She just had to stop and
pick up some root beer."

00:01:54.410 --> 00:01:55.420
"Right."

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.750
Ryan sat in his usual
chair, cracking open

00:01:57.750 --> 00:01:59.530
his first beer of the evening.

00:01:59.530 --> 00:02:02.290
He'd stop after the third,
when Sandi's nagging became

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:04.060
too much for him to handle.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:05.910
None of this was a
mystery to anyone.

00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:07.990
And that was how all
of them liked it.

00:02:07.990 --> 00:02:10.139
Playing the Apocalypse
Game for 15 years

00:02:10.139 --> 00:02:12.610
had transformed predictability
into one of the weekly game

00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:14.430
night's greatest attractions.

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:15.952
Spend some time
with your friends,

00:02:15.952 --> 00:02:17.910
play a board game you
didn't really care about,

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:20.060
and plot the
downfall of mankind.

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:21.610
Pure bliss.

00:02:21.610 --> 00:02:23.525
Cole's absence was
the only black spot

00:02:23.525 --> 00:02:26.650
on what was otherwise shaping
up to be a perfect evening.

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:29.220
She'd been more and more
scarce over the past few years,

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:31.980
as for job, which she
never described in detail,

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:34.170
been willing to say
nothing beyond "I work

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:37.420
for the government" and "I
still use my medical degree,"--

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:41.790
kept her away from home
more and more often.

00:02:41.790 --> 00:02:44.670
Even saying that much made
her visibly uncomfortable,

00:02:44.670 --> 00:02:47.040
until they all stopped asking.

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:49.840
Still, Cole missing
the Apocalypse Game

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:53.300
was a new phenomenon-- new
enough to be unnerving.

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:56.480
Out of all the players, she'd
always been the most reliable.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:59.290
"Remember the time Cole
had pneumonia," asked Ryan?

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:01.500
She missed two
sessions in a row.

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:04.820
"And then she showed up for the
third session in her bathrobe."

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:06.100
Andy laughed.

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:07.660
"Mike was so
disappointed when he

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:10.310
realized she had her
clothes on underneath it."

00:03:10.310 --> 00:03:11.780
"Those were the days."

00:03:11.780 --> 00:03:15.240
Ryan took a long swig from
his beer, amusement fading.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:16.920
"This is the third session.

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:19.090
She's never missed three."

00:03:19.090 --> 00:03:21.180
"There's a first
time for everything."

00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:22.850
"I'm worried about
her," said Elsa,

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:25.390
emerging from the kitchen
with the bowl of chips.

00:03:25.390 --> 00:03:27.090
"She's been working too much.

00:03:27.090 --> 00:03:30.730
She needs the Apocalypse Game
to take her mind off things."

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:31.814
Ryan snorted.

00:03:31.814 --> 00:03:33.480
"I'm going to give
you a second to think

00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:35.180
about what you just said."

00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:36.460
"I stand by it.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:37.770
Cole started the game.

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:40.450
She should be able to
find the time to play."

00:03:40.450 --> 00:03:43.600
"I'm sure she'll be back as
soon as she can," said Andy.

00:03:43.600 --> 00:03:44.980
"I hope so."

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:46.270
Elsa sighed.

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.780
"Maybe Mike can tell us more."

00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:51.300
"Maybe," Andy agreed dolefully.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:52.954
Silence descended.

00:03:52.954 --> 00:03:55.370
Their little social group was
just like a thousand others,

00:03:55.370 --> 00:03:57.726
all over the world, at
least superficially.

00:03:57.726 --> 00:03:59.350
A bunch of old friends
getting together

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:01.040
to play games and
talk until well

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:03.490
after any sensible
person's bed time.

00:04:03.490 --> 00:04:06.010
They met in high school, a
bunch of strange, smart kids,

00:04:06.010 --> 00:04:08.510
living on the fringes
of teenage society.

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:10.180
They clustered together
in self-defense,

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:11.866
as much as anything else.

00:04:11.866 --> 00:04:13.490
It wasn't until midway
through freshman

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:16.620
year that they all started
to actually like each other.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:19.560
The first Apocalypse Game
was practically an accident.

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.579
They've been lazing
around Cole's house, bored

00:04:21.579 --> 00:04:23.760
and restless and looking
for something to do.

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:25.770
They tried everything
from poker to Candy Land,

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:28.290
until Cole made her
characteristically mild

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:29.720
suggestion.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:32.920
"Why don't we figure out
how to destroy the world?"

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:35.250
The first scenario
was Cole's, of course.

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.750
It involved a chemical spill
wiping out the world's plankton

00:04:37.750 --> 00:04:38.520
supply.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:41.640
Without plankton, the small fish
died; without the small fish,

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:43.800
the big fish died;
without the big fish,

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:46.450
everything else in the
ocean followed suit.

00:04:46.450 --> 00:04:49.146
It was an ineffective,
inelegant apocalypse.

00:04:49.146 --> 00:04:51.270
And after they'd spent the
whole night debating it,

00:04:51.270 --> 00:04:53.110
Ryan said he could do better.

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:54.720
Elsa dared him to prove it.

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:56.300
A week later he did.

00:04:56.300 --> 00:04:59.440
Sandi took the week after
that, and so on, and so on.

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:00.620
High school ended.

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:01.960
College began.

00:05:01.960 --> 00:05:03.730
Dan and Tony moved away.

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.410
Elsa and Andy got married.

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:08.250
Cole and Mike didn't, although
they may as well have.

00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:11.600
And always, always
there was the game.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:13.200
Maybe it was a
strange way to spend

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.320
15 years of Friday nights.

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:18.820
At the end of the day,
none of them really cared.

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:20.450
The five players
took their seats

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:22.350
around the dining room table.

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.480
The chair next to Mike
remained conspicuously empty.

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:28.260
None of them could avoid
glancing at it at least once.

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:30.170
Cole's absence was palpable.

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:33.660
And it couldn't be ignored, no
matter how hard everyone tried.

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:35.590
She should've been there.

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:37.540
Mike cleared his throat.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.690
"I, uh, brought something.

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:42.880
Well, Cole sent something."

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:44.964
"Beyond her love, her
regrets, and a promise

00:05:44.964 --> 00:05:46.880
that she'll do her best
to make it next week,"

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:49.562
asked Sandi, reaching
for her second root beer.

00:05:49.562 --> 00:05:51.020
"If you run out,
we're not stopping

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:53.230
so you can go for
more," said Andy.

00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:55.640
Sandi shot him a
glare. "I know that."

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:58.580
Elsa raised a hand, stopping
the familiar argument

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:00.220
before it could begin.

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:02.050
"What did she send?"

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:03.960
"Well, Sandi was
right about Cole

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:05.920
sending her love
and her regrets.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:07.520
She also sent this."

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:09.550
Mike pulled a digital
recorder from his pocket

00:06:09.550 --> 00:06:11.910
and set it down on the
table, between the tortilla

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:13.610
chips and the veggie platter.

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:16.010
"Tonight's supposed to
be her turn, right?"

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:18.340
"Right," said Ryan dubiously.

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:18.880
"So what?

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:20.338
She's going to
present her scenario

00:06:20.338 --> 00:06:21.950
and record our discussion?"

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:22.610
"No.

00:06:22.610 --> 00:06:24.490
Cole's presenting
her own scenario.

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:26.330
I'm here to play the game."

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:28.040
Mike pressed the Play button.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:31.540
The recorder beeped once before
Cole's sweet, always slightly

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:33.430
distracted voice came
through the speaker,

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:36.020
just as clear as if she'd
actually been there.

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:37.110
"Hi guys.

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:39.110
I'm sorry I couldn't be
there in person tonight.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:43.100
But I had things I
needed to take care of.

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:45.430
This is a scenario I've
been working on for a while,

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:47.550
and I think it's pretty solid.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:49.970
"There will be beeps every
few minutes, like this one"--

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:52.780
the recorder beeped again-- "to
signal that it's time to pause

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:54.900
for discussion
before you continue.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:57.070
I think I've predicted
all your responses.

00:06:57.070 --> 00:06:59.100
You could still surprise me."

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:00.500
There was a third beep.

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:03.160
Mike leaned forward and
paused the recording.

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:05.790
"Well, is everybody
cool with this?"

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:07.830
"It's weird," said Ryan.

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:09.300
"Weird is good."

00:07:09.300 --> 00:07:11.160
Sandi giggled nervously.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:12.270
"I guess it's OK.

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:14.630
I didn't want to skip
her turn anyway."

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:16.090
"Andy, Elsa?"

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:17.200
"I'm cool with it, sure.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.710
But do you know what's on
the recording?" asked Andy?

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:21.390
"Not to be a stickler,
but scenarios

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:23.579
aren't supposed to be
shared before the game."

00:07:23.579 --> 00:07:25.120
"She recorded the
whole thing at work

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:27.245
and gave it to me before
she left for the airport,"

00:07:27.245 --> 00:07:28.080
said Mike.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.160
"I'm not a cheater.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:30.310
I didn't listen."

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:32.840
"Then I'm cool with it
too," said Elsa firmly.

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:34.400
"Play the scenario."

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:36.750
Mike pressed the button.

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:38.660
"If you're listening
to this, that

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:41.170
means you've decided
to let me take my turn.

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:42.130
Thank you.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:43.750
I really appreciate it.

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:48.030
Anyway, this is
Apocalypse Scenario #683.

00:07:48.030 --> 00:07:49.490
I've never been good with names.

00:07:49.490 --> 00:07:51.070
I'm more interested
in the science.

00:07:51.070 --> 00:07:54.260
So I call this
scenario, The Box."

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:57.490
"Sounds promising," said Sandi,
and took a swig of root beer.

00:07:57.490 --> 00:07:59.370
Ryan motioned for
her to be quiet.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:01.290
She stuck her tongue out at him.

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:03.500
Cole's voice
continued, implacably.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:06.260
"First, establishment
of the scenario.

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:09.470
The Box is based around a
man-made bacterial pandemic.

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:12.054
At the time the scenario
begins, the bacteria in question

00:08:12.054 --> 00:08:14.220
have already been released
into the human population

00:08:14.220 --> 00:08:17.190
at several geographically
distinct locations.

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:19.110
All the locations
were in North America.

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:21.190
But they all included
a very high probability

00:08:21.190 --> 00:08:23.980
of intercontinental
transmission within 24 hours,

00:08:23.980 --> 00:08:26.800
as in Andy's Ticket
to Die apocalypse."

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:28.262
"Cute," said Andy.

00:08:28.262 --> 00:08:29.970
"The bacterial strain
you're dealing with

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:31.930
was designed by a young
researcher employed

00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:35.130
by the bioterrorism division of
the United States government.

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:37.340
It was originally commissioned
under the auspices

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:39.520
of counterterrorism."

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:41.289
Cole's voiced turned
briefly bitter,

00:08:41.289 --> 00:08:44.540
causing Andy and Elsa to
exchange worried glances.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:47.720
Bitterness wasn't native
to Cole's state of being.

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:50.260
"The people in charge
lied about it, of course.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:53.320
That is vital to
understanding the scenario.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:55.650
It begins with the assumption
that if you reported

00:08:55.650 --> 00:08:58.231
the scenario to the
government, they believe you.

00:08:58.231 --> 00:08:59.730
Because the government
is the reason

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:02.500
the situation exists
in the first place."

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:03.730
The recorder beeped.

00:09:03.730 --> 00:09:05.410
Mike hit the Pause button.

00:09:05.410 --> 00:09:06.730
"There's our set-up."

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:08.950
"It's pretty simplistic,
especially for Cole,"

00:09:08.950 --> 00:09:09.960
said Ryan.

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:11.170
"Somebody drops a test tube.

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:12.878
Somebody else tells
the people in charge.

00:09:12.878 --> 00:09:15.440
And everything gets mopped
up, with minimal loss of life.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:16.970
The world doesn't end."

00:09:16.970 --> 00:09:19.470
"Nobody dropped a
test tube," said Elsa.

00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:21.650
"She said it was released
into the human population

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:26.130
in 'several geographically
diverse locations,' and implied

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:28.690
that they were chosen to create
the widest possible infection

00:09:28.690 --> 00:09:29.410
pattern.

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:31.730
This thing was
intentionally released."

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:34.440
"The government angle still
makes it simple," said Andy.

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:35.670
Sandi shrugged.

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:37.300
"So it will be a
short apocalypse.

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:38.570
Go ahead and press Play, Mike.

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:40.410
I want to hear what comes next."

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:42.710
Mike nodded and
pressed the button.

00:09:42.710 --> 00:09:45.780
The bitterness was gone, when
Cole resumed her explanation.

00:09:45.780 --> 00:09:49.520
Instead, she sounded cheerful,
if a little over tired.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.250
"Second, elaboration
of the scenario.

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:54.160
You're looking at a
bacterial infection based

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:56.790
on the combination of whooping
cough and tuberculosis,

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:58.980
just like Ryan's
No Air apocalypse.

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:00.690
Only this time, the
bacteria has been

00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:03.050
tailored for
antibiotic resistance.

00:10:03.050 --> 00:10:05.730
"The first generation has
an artificially long latency

00:10:05.730 --> 00:10:08.120
built in, to allow
for extensive spread.

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:10.070
Once the first
generation of bacteria

00:10:10.070 --> 00:10:12.000
have incubated to
maturity in human lungs,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.405
the latency will be halved,
until the final projected

00:10:14.405 --> 00:10:16.780
generation, where it will
default to the standard latency

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:18.420
period for whooping cough.

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:20.540
Symptoms include coughing,
runny nose, headache,

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:22.998
difficulty breathing, muscular
spasms, secondary pneumonia,

00:10:22.998 --> 00:10:24.800
and, of course, death.

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:26.530
Fatality estimates
place the death toll

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:29.920
at approximately 91% of
the infected population.

00:10:29.920 --> 00:10:32.870
It's impossible to accurately
project susceptibility.

00:10:32.870 --> 00:10:35.760
The projections indicate that
as much as 80% of the human race

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:38.610
could be infected by the
end of the second latency."

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:39.270
Beep.

00:10:39.270 --> 00:10:40.750
Pause.

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:41.250
"OK.

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:42.570
That's charming."

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:44.200
Sandi wrinkled her nose.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.320
"Has Cole off her
meds or something?

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:49.420
She's not normally this
nasty with her scenarios."

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:51.360
Mike didn't say anything.

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.360
He reached almost
mechanically for the chips,

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:55.130
scooping up a handful.

00:10:55.130 --> 00:10:56.691
His eyes look haunted.

00:10:56.691 --> 00:10:58.440
Something about that
look frightened Andy,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:01.270
in ways he wasn't sure
he could put into words.

00:11:01.270 --> 00:11:02.970
Something was wrong.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:05.835
"Mike," he said, "you OK, buddy?

00:11:05.835 --> 00:11:07.640
Is Cole OK?"

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:09.520
"She's been working
a lot lately."

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:11.300
Mike forced a laugh.

00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:13.390
"She's just
stressed, that's all.

00:11:13.390 --> 00:11:14.716
Let's keep going."

00:11:14.716 --> 00:11:16.590
He hit the button before
anyone could object.

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:18.550
And Cole spoke again.

00:11:18.550 --> 00:11:22.970
"Three-- three,
explanation of apocalypse

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:24.450
stemming from scenario.

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:25.700
Buckle up, guys.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:27.870
Here's where the
real game starts.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:31.340
"See, this researcher, she was
recruited right out of college.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:33.910
Her scholarship
to medical school,

00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:35.930
wasn't a scholarship,
not really;

00:11:35.930 --> 00:11:37.100
it was a government loan.

00:11:37.100 --> 00:11:38.930
They'd pay for
everything and she'd

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:40.950
go to work for them
when she graduated.

00:11:40.950 --> 00:11:44.160
They wanted her that much,
because she was that good."

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:46.860
Something like pride
crept into Cole's voice.

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:49.420
"They knew she'd be able
to change the world."

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:52.800
Elsa's hand clamped down on
Andy's elbow, squeezing hard.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:54.950
None of them said anything.

00:11:54.950 --> 00:11:57.370
"For a while, she was
happy with the deal.

00:11:57.370 --> 00:12:00.050
She thought she was protecting
the world against the bad guys.

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:01.840
That she could stave
off the apocalypse

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.400
she'd been worrying about
since she was in high school.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.590
She tore viruses and bacteria
apart and recombined in ways

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:10.290
no one else has ever
been able to accomplish.

00:12:10.290 --> 00:12:11.110
"She read.

00:12:11.110 --> 00:12:12.470
She researched.

00:12:12.470 --> 00:12:14.980
She was going to
change the world.

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:16.476
Only it turned out she had.

00:12:16.476 --> 00:12:18.850
Because she started hearing
about this outbreak in Korea,

00:12:18.850 --> 00:12:21.370
that perfectly mirrored
one of her projects,

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:24.232
one of her defensive projects.

00:12:24.232 --> 00:12:25.690
People were dying
of something that

00:12:25.690 --> 00:12:28.990
sounded a lot like her enhanced
strain of bubonic plague.

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:32.150
"She went to her superiors
and asked them-- asked them

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:34.040
if they were going to send help.

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:37.040
And they told her to go back to
her lab and get back to work."

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:39.670
"I saw that on the
news," whispered Elsa.

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:41.880
So many people died."

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:43.260
Cole continued.

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:45.277
"She got scared
then, our researcher.

00:12:45.277 --> 00:12:47.360
And she started really
looking at the things she'd

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:50.880
been working on, the things that
were supposed to help people.

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:53.110
Only they weren't
helping people at all.

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:54.270
They were hurting them.

00:12:54.270 --> 00:12:56.380
And everyone said
that was OK because we

00:12:56.380 --> 00:12:57.427
weren't the only ones.

00:12:57.427 --> 00:12:59.260
"Every government in
the world was doing it.

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:00.730
And that made it OK.

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:01.970
That made it necessary.

00:13:01.970 --> 00:13:04.980
Because if we didn't build
it, someone else would."

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:07.390
She stopped, seeming to
her place for a moment,

00:13:07.390 --> 00:13:11.230
before repeating,
"Someone else would.

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:14.650
It wasn't something she could
stop by walking away, you know.

00:13:14.650 --> 00:13:16.380
It was going to happen.

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:18.080
We'd made it inevitable.

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:19.939
She'd made it inevitable.

00:13:19.939 --> 00:13:21.480
"So maybe the best
thing she could do

00:13:21.480 --> 00:13:23.950
was stop it all before
it got even worse.

00:13:23.950 --> 00:13:26.190
Stop it the only
way she knew how.

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:28.260
Stop the whole damn
arms race for awhile

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:30.490
and give everyone a
chance to breathe.

00:13:30.490 --> 00:13:34.330
For certain values
of every one, anyway.

00:13:34.330 --> 00:13:36.350
Because if she didn't--

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:38.820
"Things had been getting
worse for a long time.

00:13:38.820 --> 00:13:40.165
Everybody knows that.

00:13:40.165 --> 00:13:42.160
If humanity isn't
stopped, they're

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:44.950
going to kill the planet,
not just themselves.

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:46.920
Someone had to do something.

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:50.120
She was just the one watching
when the time finally came."

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:50.700
Beep.

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:51.660
Pause.

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:54.620
"This is sick," said
Sandi, glaring at Mike.

00:13:54.620 --> 00:13:56.030
"Why is she doing this?

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:57.910
There's not even
anything to discuss.

00:13:57.910 --> 00:14:01.554
It's just sick, Mike."

00:14:01.554 --> 00:14:03.720
Elsa worried her lip between
her teeth for a moment,

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:07.960
before saying, "Cole never
told us who she worked for."

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:09.510
"No."

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:11.130
Mike's voice was bleak.

00:14:11.130 --> 00:14:12.670
"She wasn't allowed to.

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:15.140
They made her sign
a lot of papers."

00:14:15.140 --> 00:14:19.080
"A lot of papers in exchange
for what?" asked Andy.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:20.570
"Medical school."

00:14:20.570 --> 00:14:22.810
Mike pressed the button.

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:25.010
"The release happened
six days ago.

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:27.820
The infection has a
latency of 23 days.

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:30.990
Additional releases
are ongoing because--"

00:14:30.990 --> 00:14:32.990
Cole stopped again,
before starting back up,

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:35.530
sounding more and more
like a broken marionette.

00:14:35.530 --> 00:14:37.164
She was running down.

00:14:37.164 --> 00:14:39.330
"Because the government
funded the original project,

00:14:39.330 --> 00:14:40.870
they might be able
to find a vaccine

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:42.700
if they start
looking immediately.

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:44.910
It wouldn't be hard to
type the bacterial strain.

00:14:44.910 --> 00:14:47.790
And there are only a few
researchers working with it.

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:50.592
They don't know about all
the modifications that I--

00:14:50.592 --> 00:14:53.910
that she-- that were made.

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.370
"They'd need to
start right away.

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:58.230
But there's a catch."

00:14:58.230 --> 00:15:00.974
"Isn't there
always?" asked Mike.

00:15:00.974 --> 00:15:02.640
"The researcher who
created the disease,

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:04.710
she's listening in on
all the big channels

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:06.430
and a lot of the small ones.

00:15:06.430 --> 00:15:08.460
She has people feeding
her information.

00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:11.280
People who have really good
reason to be loyal to her.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:13.890
People who see the
same solution she does.

00:15:13.890 --> 00:15:17.110
"And if she hears a whisper
from any government, anywhere,

00:15:17.110 --> 00:15:19.270
that links this pandemic
to her research,

00:15:19.270 --> 00:15:22.080
she'll release the second
project she worked on,

00:15:22.080 --> 00:15:23.530
the bad one."

00:15:23.530 --> 00:15:26.200
"This isn't the bad one?"

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:28.270
Ryan sounded incredulous.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.090
"I mean, come on, Cole."

00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:32.030
"Here's where things
get dicey, guys.

00:15:32.030 --> 00:15:33.840
See, the second virus
isn't bacterial.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:36.910
It's an actual virus based on
a hemorrhagic out of Africa,

00:15:36.910 --> 00:15:38.490
called Lassa fever.

00:15:38.490 --> 00:15:40.670
It's got a long latency
and a high mortality.

00:15:40.670 --> 00:15:42.750
And that's without clever
virologists playing

00:15:42.750 --> 00:15:44.210
with the way it works.

00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:46.104
"And this one hasn't
got a vaccine.

00:15:46.104 --> 00:15:48.020
Although it does have a
nasty little interlock

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:50.189
with the vaccine for
the bacterial strain.

00:15:50.189 --> 00:15:52.480
If you would have been immune
to the original pandemic,

00:15:52.480 --> 00:15:54.810
either naturally or
due to immunization,

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:57.640
you'll get the second
virus and you'll die."

00:15:57.640 --> 00:15:59.130
Cole sighed deeply.

00:15:59.130 --> 00:16:00.560
"I'm sorry about that."

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:02.690
"Is she crazy?" demanded Sandi?

00:16:02.690 --> 00:16:05.010
"I don't know," said Ryan.

00:16:05.010 --> 00:16:06.670
Cole's laughter
startled them all.

00:16:06.670 --> 00:16:08.195
Even Mike, who
jumped in his chair

00:16:08.195 --> 00:16:10.620
and nearly knocked
over Sandi's root beer.

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:13.930
It was a brittle, jagged
sound, like broken glass.

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:14.430
"OK.

00:16:14.430 --> 00:16:14.930
OK.

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:16.440
I give, you guys," she said.

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:19.300
"This 'oh, I have a friend,'
shit is so high school,

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:20.080
isn't it?

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:21.320
I built the virus.

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:22.450
I built them both.

00:16:22.450 --> 00:16:23.680
"The scenario is still valid.

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:26.760
The releases started last
week, Manhattan, San Francisco,

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:29.320
and best of all, Disney World.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.620
I put it in misters, just like
Elsa's Black Fungus apocalypse.

00:16:32.620 --> 00:16:33.610
"Thanks for that, Elsa.

00:16:33.610 --> 00:16:35.220
It works great."

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:36.290
Elsa looked ill.

00:16:36.290 --> 00:16:38.110
Cole kept talking.

00:16:38.110 --> 00:16:39.630
"I love you guys.

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:41.570
You're the best
friends I've ever had.

00:16:41.570 --> 00:16:43.670
I mean you may be the only
friends I've ever had,

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:45.680
the only real ones anyway.

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:48.000
That's why I'm leaving
this up to you.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.070
"I vaccinated you all against
the first disease months ago.

00:16:51.070 --> 00:16:53.600
You're probably the safest
people on the planet.

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:55.340
Yes, even you Sandi.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:16:56.510
I know you slept with Mike.

00:16:56.510 --> 00:16:58.620
But I don't really care
about that anymore.

00:16:58.620 --> 00:17:00.820
It's too trivial a concern."

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.490
Sandi and Mike
exchanged a glance.

00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:03.940
Her eyes wide and horrified.

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:05.630
His, merely resigned.

00:17:05.630 --> 00:17:07.510
Cole kept talking.

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:09.900
"You're all going to live
through what comes next.

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:11.290
It won't be fun.

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:12.540
But you'll live.

00:17:12.540 --> 00:17:14.369
"I knew you wouldn't
want to do it alone.

00:17:14.369 --> 00:17:16.319
You're always more
social than I was.

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:18.839
So I've arranged to have a box
couriered to Elsa and Andy's

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:20.359
place tonight, during the game.

00:17:20.359 --> 00:17:24.040
"Inside, you'll find 10 doses
of vaccine for each of you.

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:26.079
Use them however you want.

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:28.950
Save your family, or your
friends, or your doctor.

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:30.420
It's up to you.

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:32.250
"You can even give
them to the government.

00:17:32.250 --> 00:17:34.560
And if you do, I'll die
with you because I'm

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:37.640
immune to the first
pandemic, just like you are."

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:39.720
Cole's voice turned wistful.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:42.135
"I wish I could have given
you the scenario in person.

00:17:42.135 --> 00:17:45.080
I think it's the best one
I've ever put together.

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:46.570
I really wanted to.

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:48.850
But in the end, I
couldn't risk it.

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:51.577
I love you all, you all so much.

00:17:51.577 --> 00:17:53.410
"I hope you'll find the
answer that's right.

00:17:53.410 --> 00:17:56.170
Because to be honest, I can't.

00:17:56.170 --> 00:17:58.120
All I can do is end
the world and let

00:17:58.120 --> 00:18:00.920
you decide how much
of it survives.

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:03.500
This is Cole Evans signing out."

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:04.850
A pause.

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:06.560
And then in a
whisper they all had

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:09.860
to strain hear, "Forgive me."

00:18:09.860 --> 00:18:11.990
The recorder beeped
one more time.

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:13.680
Silence fell.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:15.620
Ryan was the first to react.

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:16.870
He laughed nervously.

00:18:16.870 --> 00:18:17.931
"OK wow.

00:18:17.931 --> 00:18:19.930
That's the best mind fuck
we've had in a while."

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:21.840
He points to Cole.

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:24.780
"I don't think she was
kidding," said Elsa.

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:28.130
"We haven't answered the
scenario yet guys," said Mike.

00:18:28.130 --> 00:18:29.820
"Do we call the
government and die or do

00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:31.611
we condemn millions of
people because we're

00:18:31.611 --> 00:18:33.560
too chicken to pick up a phone?"

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:36.540
"Dude, did you really sleep
with Sandi?" asked Ryan.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.160
Mike didn't answer.

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:40.770
"Won't calling the government
mean killing even more people,"

00:18:40.770 --> 00:18:41.740
asked Andy.

00:18:41.740 --> 00:18:44.180
She said the second
virus was worse."

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:46.100
"We don't know if
that," said Mike.

00:18:46.100 --> 00:18:48.180
"Maybe there's only one virus."

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:51.840
"Because Cole was always an
underachiever." said Ryan.

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:54.120
"If she says there's a
second virus in the scenario,

00:18:54.120 --> 00:18:56.190
there's a second
virus in the scenario.

00:18:56.190 --> 00:18:58.850
I'm just not buying the
idea that it's real life."

00:18:58.850 --> 00:19:01.220
"Are you willing to
risk it?" asked Elsa.

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:03.590
"We're not risking
anything," snapped Sandi.

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:04.270
"It's a game.

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:05.290
It's a stupid game.

00:19:05.290 --> 00:19:07.960
And that's all its ever been and
that's also we're going to be.

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:09.760
"Stop taking this so seriously.

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:11.280
Cole is just messing with us.

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:12.740
That's all."

00:19:12.740 --> 00:19:15.000
The doorbell rang.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.670
Silence fell again, thick and
heavy as a curtain going down.

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:20.970
Elsa looked around the group,
meeting everyone's eyes

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:22.220
in turn.

00:19:22.220 --> 00:19:24.600
Then she slowly pushed the
chair back from the table,

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:28.130
stood, and walked
to answer the door.

00:19:28.130 --> 00:19:30.460
She was halfway across the
room when the person outside

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:33.270
began to cough.

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:35.460
So that is The Box.

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:37.320
I did that to my
friends for a year.

00:19:37.320 --> 00:19:39.290
Like I'd literally go,
if you have no reason

00:19:39.290 --> 00:19:42.440
to believe I didn't just wipe
out mankind, what would you do?

00:19:42.440 --> 00:19:44.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.125
I'm a great friend.

00:19:46.125 --> 00:19:48.250
My friend Sean, said he
would go out in the street,

00:19:48.250 --> 00:19:50.820
vaccinate first 10 strangers
he saw, and then eat a bullet.

00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:51.320
Because.

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:54.110
If I actually done this,
he had failed somehow

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:56.530
to stop me before I
could get that far.

00:19:56.530 --> 00:19:58.780
And I went, that's
the best response.

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:02.141
So does anybody
have any questions?

00:20:02.141 --> 00:20:02.640
OK.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.260
So everybody's freaking
out about Ebola.

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:08.480
Ebola.

00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:09.620
Ebola is nasty.

00:20:09.620 --> 00:20:10.620
We do not like Ebola.

00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:12.590
It's very tragic that it's
killing a lot of people.

00:20:12.590 --> 00:20:15.006
And it's really too bad that
we don't have a good vaccine.

00:20:15.006 --> 00:20:19.890
But the problem with the Ebola
is that it has a very low R0.

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:22.480
Now, the R0 is how many
people you can conceivably

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:25.910
pass the virus along to before
you die a horrible death

00:20:25.910 --> 00:20:28.820
or are somehow no longer
infectious, but still alive.

00:20:28.820 --> 00:20:31.020
If you manage the
second, congratulations.

00:20:31.020 --> 00:20:35.440
The R0 of Ebola,
on average, is two.

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:37.470
So you can pass it
to two more people.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:39.920
And that's with an
absolutely idealized chain

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:41.000
of transmission.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.310
So you managed to bleed,
spit, cry, or piss

00:20:43.310 --> 00:20:45.500
on two other people
before you're just dead.

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:47.750
This is why I usually tell
folks that are not actually

00:20:47.750 --> 00:20:50.041
medical professionals, that
if you want to avoid Ebola,

00:20:50.041 --> 00:20:52.300
just don't lick people.

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:55.360
The flu, on the
other hand-- and this

00:20:55.360 --> 00:20:57.630
is why we're all getting
our flu shots this year,

00:20:57.630 --> 00:21:00.430
unless we have a good
medical reason not to.

00:21:00.430 --> 00:21:02.652
Any guesses on
the R0 of the flu?

00:21:02.652 --> 00:21:03.475
AUDIENCE: 500.

00:21:03.475 --> 00:21:04.100
MIRA GRANT: No.

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:05.240
Not quite that good.

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:09.510
But it has an
estimated R0 of 10.

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:12.430
So every case of the flu
is good for a minimum

00:21:12.430 --> 00:21:14.620
of 10 additional cases.

00:21:14.620 --> 00:21:16.320
And what's really
great about the flu is

00:21:16.320 --> 00:21:19.220
that it is, unlike Ebola,
which is purely body fluid

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:21.770
transmissible,
fomite transmissible.

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:23.340
Fomites mean that
anything that's

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:26.880
been touched by our initial
carrier, anything at all,

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:30.240
is now also infectious and
can add to that R0 of 10.

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:32.760
So we've got 10 from the
people you breathe on

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:36.090
and then an additional three
from stuff you touched.

00:21:36.090 --> 00:21:37.251
Yeah.

00:21:37.251 --> 00:21:39.470
So get your flu shots.

00:21:39.470 --> 00:21:42.950
10,000 Americans will die of
the flu this year, 10,000.

00:21:42.950 --> 00:21:44.950
That's actually not a
good reason to be smiling.

00:21:44.950 --> 00:21:47.690
I just always am when I'm
talking about the flu.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:49.850
It's like a nervous tic.

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:50.820
So that's R0.

00:21:50.820 --> 00:21:51.760
The R0 is great.

00:21:51.760 --> 00:21:53.890
The R0 is the reason
that sexually transmitted

00:21:53.890 --> 00:21:56.190
diseases are
sexually transmitted

00:21:56.190 --> 00:21:57.975
and not caught in other ways.

00:21:57.975 --> 00:21:59.349
They usually have a very low R0.

00:21:59.349 --> 00:22:01.640
AUDIENCE: So you wrote that
song about the Black Death,

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:02.960
like 10 years ago.

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:05.280
And just recently, I
started seeing articles

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:08.046
that are vindicating what you
were espousing in that song.

00:22:08.046 --> 00:22:09.170
How do you feel about that?

00:22:09.170 --> 00:22:11.040
MIRA GRANT: I feel
real good because I

00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:12.559
had a-- the song
she's referring to,

00:22:12.559 --> 00:22:13.850
the song about the Black Death.

00:22:13.850 --> 00:22:16.240
It's actually called
the "Black Death."

00:22:16.240 --> 00:22:20.420
And it is roughly eight minute
long, schoolhouse, rock-style

00:22:20.420 --> 00:22:23.370
song, explaining why
the causative agent

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:25.350
for the Black Death
in Europe was probably

00:22:25.350 --> 00:22:28.190
not yersinia pestis, or the
bubonic plague bacterium,

00:22:28.190 --> 00:22:29.430
as most people believed.

00:22:29.430 --> 00:22:31.699
But was, instead, an
unidentified hemorrhagic fever,

00:22:31.699 --> 00:22:33.990
that had traveled up the Nile
River to the Middle East,

00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:35.750
and then made the jump
to Messina, Italy.

00:22:35.750 --> 00:22:38.240
But I literally took
all of the science

00:22:38.240 --> 00:22:40.150
on the side of the
hemorrhagic fever theory,

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:42.550
or rather about
80% of the science

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:45.360
on the hemorrhagic fever
theory, and boiled it down

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:47.260
into cheerful rhyming verses.

00:22:47.260 --> 00:22:49.060
Like, well, we
blamed it on the rats

00:22:49.060 --> 00:22:50.420
and we blamed it on the fleas.

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:53.300
We were ignoring crucial facts
about the speed of the disease.

00:22:53.300 --> 00:22:54.990
And I think it's time
we call for a more

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:55.866
thorough inquisition.

00:22:55.866 --> 00:22:57.906
Because it's clear that
the Black Death possessed

00:22:57.906 --> 00:22:59.349
a droplet-based transmission.

00:22:59.349 --> 00:23:01.265
Now, a droplet-based
transition means I sneeze

00:23:01.265 --> 00:23:02.190
and then you die.

00:23:02.190 --> 00:23:03.680
It's a fairly common vector.

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:06.450
And we think that's largely
why the quarantine developed

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:08.320
to protect us from
diseases and to help

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:10.980
to keep your family from
dying of my sneezes.

00:23:10.980 --> 00:23:13.124
So it's eight minutes of that.

00:23:13.124 --> 00:23:15.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:20.680
And it goes into a lot of very
strong evidentiary support

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:22.400
for the hemorrhagic
fever theory.

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:24.400
The main reason I think
we should be considering

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:27.280
this information isn't because
we're somehow magically going

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:29.889
to bring back the thousands
of people if we say,

00:23:29.889 --> 00:23:31.180
oh, it's wasn't bubonic plague.

00:23:31.180 --> 00:23:32.750
You can get out
of your grave now.

00:23:32.750 --> 00:23:36.580
But because when we take
this stuff just as a given,

00:23:36.580 --> 00:23:39.500
when we say, oh, it absolutely
was this bacteria that we

00:23:39.500 --> 00:23:43.480
can easily cure today, we become
a lot less respectful of things

00:23:43.480 --> 00:23:47.170
like plague pits, that
are still all over Europe.

00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:49.640
Some of which are in good
permafrost conditions

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:53.600
for the preservation of
virological sustainability.

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:57.250
You crack one of those puppies
open, we could all die.

00:23:57.250 --> 00:24:00.660
There was a study published,
I think, four years ago now,

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:04.510
where this one German consortium
said, yes, absolute proof.

00:24:04.510 --> 00:24:06.960
We did a core sample
in a known plague pit.

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:09.310
And we found yersinia
pestis bacterium.

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:11.770
So everyone who says that
it's not yersinia pestis

00:24:11.770 --> 00:24:13.527
is wrong and can go home.

00:24:13.527 --> 00:24:15.610
And by the way, it's totally
OK for the people who

00:24:15.610 --> 00:24:17.460
funded the study to
dig up the plague pits

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:20.310
and run a high-speed rail right
through the middle of them.

00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:22.690
We all live in California.

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:25.700
If you've lived in California
for more than eight months,

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:28.890
you have been exposed to the
yersinia pestis bacteria.

00:24:28.890 --> 00:24:31.970
You probably have it in
the pulp of your teeth.

00:24:31.970 --> 00:24:34.330
Because that's one of the
places that it builds up.

00:24:34.330 --> 00:24:37.280
So if I were to yank a molar
from every person in this room,

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:39.940
before Google security
arrested me for assault,

00:24:39.940 --> 00:24:43.410
I could test them and find
proof that yersinia pestis was

00:24:43.410 --> 00:24:44.840
endemic on the Google campus.

00:24:44.840 --> 00:24:49.570
And thus, clearly, that is what
had killed you all, and not

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:52.000
the crazy woman with the pliers.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.840
So there's very strong
evidence for hemorrhagic fever.

00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:57.900
There's very little
evidence for bubonic plague.

00:24:57.900 --> 00:25:00.860
There's actually more evidence
on the hemorrhagic fever

00:25:00.860 --> 00:25:03.620
side of things, which is kind
of fascinating when you really

00:25:03.620 --> 00:25:04.970
start digging into it.

00:25:04.970 --> 00:25:07.830
But everyone accepts that
it was bubonic plague.

00:25:07.830 --> 00:25:08.380
Why?

00:25:08.380 --> 00:25:10.820
Because their third grade
history teacher told them

00:25:10.820 --> 00:25:12.930
it was bubonic plague.

00:25:12.930 --> 00:25:15.990
And that is very sloppy
thinking scientifically.

00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:18.881
Now, as she mentioned
here, in the front row,

00:25:18.881 --> 00:25:20.380
in the last problem
couple of years,

00:25:20.380 --> 00:25:22.690
as more people started
really looking at this

00:25:22.690 --> 00:25:27.390
because somebody finally
realized, wait, plague pit?

00:25:27.390 --> 00:25:31.660
Let's not dig that up.

00:25:31.660 --> 00:25:32.640
Hey.

00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:34.550
So they started
really looking at it

00:25:34.550 --> 00:25:37.670
and realizing that there's
some strong evidence

00:25:37.670 --> 00:25:41.710
to support the idea that
this was a novel virus.

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:44.210
And not only that, but
it was a novel virus

00:25:44.210 --> 00:25:47.720
we have not encountered
again, as yet.

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:49.840
Which is part of what is
driving up the interest,

00:25:49.840 --> 00:25:51.710
as more and more
novel viruses are

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:53.255
emerging from their
natural habitats

00:25:53.255 --> 00:25:55.370
and interacting with humanity.

00:25:55.370 --> 00:25:59.000
If we assume that the
Black Death was something

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.640
that made the transition from
the Middle East, to Europe--

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:07.250
and we have a very strong
chain to prove that-- we have

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:09.760
the landing and departure
records for the ship

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:12.030
that is widely accepted
as the first point

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:14.110
of entry for the Black
Death into Europe.

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:19.230
And it sailed out of
Jerusalem, into Messina, Italy.

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:19.730
Yes.

00:26:19.730 --> 00:26:22.000
We've got great support.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:23.730
That could come back.

00:26:23.730 --> 00:26:25.382
It could come to visit us again.

00:26:25.382 --> 00:26:27.340
And we would be looking
at a hemorrhagic fever,

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:30.340
with a fatality rate
of approximately 97%,

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:36.131
an R0 of an estimated 15 to
25, and a latency period of 31

00:26:36.131 --> 00:26:36.630
days.

00:26:39.190 --> 00:26:39.690
Yay.

00:26:39.690 --> 00:26:42.820
So I'm very excited that
all this is coming up.

00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:43.610
It's great.

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:44.960
I love the Black Dance song.

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:46.190
I have a huge amount
of affection for it

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:48.200
because that song is the
reason the CDC started

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:49.741
talking to me at
all when I was doing

00:26:49.741 --> 00:26:52.080
the research my
first zombie novel.

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:55.110
I called and said hi.

00:26:55.110 --> 00:26:56.294
My name is Seanan McGuire.

00:26:56.294 --> 00:26:57.710
Because that is
my real name and I

00:26:57.710 --> 00:26:59.950
had not become Mira Grant yet.

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:00.450
Hi.

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:01.220
My name is Seanan McGuire.

00:27:01.220 --> 00:27:02.690
And I want to write
a book about zombies.

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:03.800
And do you have any
researchers that

00:27:03.800 --> 00:27:05.799
would be willing to talk
about diseases with me?

00:27:05.799 --> 00:27:08.010
And they were like, no.

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:09.560
This is the CDC.

00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:12.110
We don't get-- Oh.

00:27:12.110 --> 00:27:13.050
OK.

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:15.926
Well, anybody says that
they might be willing to,

00:27:15.926 --> 00:27:17.300
can I leave an
email address just

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:18.810
in case someone's like bored?

00:27:18.810 --> 00:27:19.610
Oh, fine.

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:21.234
We'll take your info
if you'll go away.

00:27:21.234 --> 00:27:24.290
And so I start spelling my name
and the lady goes wait, wait.

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:26.798
That's how you pronounce that?

00:27:26.798 --> 00:27:27.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:29.590
Are you the Black Death girl?

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:31.130
I'm like, what?

00:27:31.130 --> 00:27:35.060
And she says, did you write
a song about the Black Death?

00:27:35.060 --> 00:27:36.337
Yes.

00:27:36.337 --> 00:27:37.670
I'm going to put you on speaker.

00:27:37.670 --> 00:27:38.590
Prove it.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:41.100
So I had to say the
entire Black Death

00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:44.790
song for the secretarial
pool at the CDC.

00:27:44.790 --> 00:27:46.600
And then magically,
eight doctors

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:48.240
were happy to talk to me.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:52.930
So a great deal of
affection for that song.

00:27:52.930 --> 00:27:55.270
AUDIENCE: How did you
get into diseases?

00:27:55.270 --> 00:27:57.920
MIRA GRANT: Well, I caught some.

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:00.350
And that was pretty neat.

00:28:00.350 --> 00:28:02.460
I have OCD.

00:28:02.460 --> 00:28:06.670
So I have some of the issues
that people with OCD have.

00:28:06.670 --> 00:28:09.110
And I realized, when
I was in high school,

00:28:09.110 --> 00:28:11.764
that I was verging on
becoming a germaphobe.

00:28:11.764 --> 00:28:13.180
That I was starting
to get really,

00:28:13.180 --> 00:28:15.950
really twitchy and upset
when anyone was sick,

00:28:15.950 --> 00:28:18.579
with anything, anywhere near me.

00:28:18.579 --> 00:28:20.120
And at that point,
I kind of sat down

00:28:20.120 --> 00:28:21.750
and went, OK, this is nascent.

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:24.834
This is becoming an obsession.

00:28:24.834 --> 00:28:26.750
We can either have it
be the kind of obsession

00:28:26.750 --> 00:28:29.090
where I wind up
living in a bubble

00:28:29.090 --> 00:28:31.030
or we can have it become
the kind of obsession

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:34.130
where I think that jamming my
hand into a bucket of maggots

00:28:34.130 --> 00:28:36.040
is fun.

00:28:36.040 --> 00:28:37.160
Bubble?

00:28:37.160 --> 00:28:38.870
Maggots?

00:28:38.870 --> 00:28:40.370
Bubble?

00:28:40.370 --> 00:28:42.550
I like maggots.

00:28:42.550 --> 00:28:43.992
Bubble?

00:28:43.992 --> 00:28:45.600
Oh, let's go over there.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:47.162
So I started reading
up on diseases

00:28:47.162 --> 00:28:48.870
and learning everything
I could because I

00:28:48.870 --> 00:28:51.840
wanted to shift to
burgeoning obsession

00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:53.170
over to understanding.

00:28:53.170 --> 00:28:55.377
Basically, if I knew
enough about them,

00:28:55.377 --> 00:28:56.710
I would still be afraid of them.

00:28:56.710 --> 00:28:58.660
But it would be a
respectful fear, rather than

00:28:58.660 --> 00:29:00.640
in irrational fear.

00:29:00.640 --> 00:29:02.890
And I was lucky in that
I did it at the time.

00:29:02.890 --> 00:29:04.860
I knew several
folks that did, not

00:29:04.860 --> 00:29:07.240
who were in a couple
of counseling circles

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:10.350
with me, in group therapy,
who can't touch things now.

00:29:10.350 --> 00:29:11.830
Like they can't pee in public.

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:15.980
They can't share food because
they've gotten so frightened.

00:29:15.980 --> 00:29:18.310
Whereas I'm like,
nah, I know the odds.

00:29:18.310 --> 00:29:19.210
It's all good.

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:20.830
Let's get tapeworms.

00:29:20.830 --> 00:29:22.035
It's a party.

00:29:22.035 --> 00:29:23.160
So I started studying them.

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:24.960
I kind of thought about
going to medical school

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:25.751
for a little while.

00:29:25.751 --> 00:29:27.760
But the money just
wasn't there, sadly.

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:30.350
If it had been, I think I'd be
working for EIS by this point

00:29:30.350 --> 00:29:33.510
and having a lovely time,
going off into the jungle,

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:36.362
and kicking things to see
if they're full of Ebola.

00:29:36.362 --> 00:29:38.320
We still don't know where
the Ebola comes from.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:41.580
So that is an ongoing
party that just is rolling.

00:29:41.580 --> 00:29:44.770
It eats up EIS operatives
like nobody's business.

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:48.260
But viruses and diseases and
parasites are just fascinating.

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:49.770
Like they're older than we are.

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:51.800
Some of them are so old
that they are actually

00:29:51.800 --> 00:29:53.490
a part of our DNA.

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:55.790
If you hear people talk
about junk DNA, the things

00:29:55.790 --> 00:29:59.170
that our bodies intentionally
manufacture in our little DNA

00:29:59.170 --> 00:30:02.060
factories, and then carry
around, that don't do anything,

00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:05.890
some of them are viruses that
are older than the human race.

00:30:05.890 --> 00:30:08.200
That we've just kind of
programed in there and now

00:30:08.200 --> 00:30:10.171
carry around with us.

00:30:10.171 --> 00:30:10.920
We don't know why.

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:12.330
We don't know what
they're doing.

00:30:12.330 --> 00:30:15.092
We don't know what
they might do some day.

00:30:15.092 --> 00:30:16.800
There's always the
possibility that we're

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:19.040
going to have a genetic
therapy or we're

00:30:19.040 --> 00:30:20.770
going to modify
something in such a way

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:22.960
that it unlocks one
of these protoviruses

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:24.670
and we all turn
into snake people.

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:25.700
We don't know.

00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:27.310
It's the best thing.

00:30:27.310 --> 00:30:29.970
It's like hacking
the human genome.

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:30.630
And I love it.

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:32.140
It makes me so happy.

00:30:32.140 --> 00:30:36.140
And it makes it really hard
to have dinner with me,

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:38.040
really, really hard.

00:30:38.040 --> 00:30:39.230
