There's at least one
character whose life

00:53:52.530 --> 00:53:55.720
was saved by a coin flip, which
means that another character's

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:58.134
life was ended by
the-- no, there's two.

00:53:58.134 --> 00:54:00.550
There's two characters in the
same series, where I'm like.

00:54:00.550 --> 00:54:04.280
I could kill person A, or I
could kill person B, A or B,

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:06.000
A or-- I'm going to flip a coin.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.790
Sorry.

00:54:08.790 --> 00:54:11.070
Which is interesting
because the coin really

00:54:11.070 --> 00:54:13.260
likes killing white dudes.

00:54:13.260 --> 00:54:14.354
I appreciate that.

00:54:14.354 --> 00:54:15.770
I literally had a
position where I

00:54:15.770 --> 00:54:19.942
had a Chinese American and
a Russian Jewish American.

00:54:19.942 --> 00:54:20.900
And I flipped the coin.

00:54:20.900 --> 00:54:22.274
It was like kill
the Russian guy.

00:54:22.274 --> 00:54:24.584
Oh, sorry, Dave.

00:54:24.584 --> 00:54:26.500
The person I named him
after was very put out.

00:54:27.980 --> 00:54:30.450
So I'm not I'm not as
foreshadowy as Sarah.

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:32.910
But Sarah Rees
Brennan, who is lovely.

00:54:32.910 --> 00:54:34.280
She's absolutely splendid.

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:37.280
She's this tall.

00:54:37.280 --> 00:54:38.770
I'm only exaggerating a little.

00:54:38.770 --> 00:54:40.410
She's actually 6 foot.

00:54:40.410 --> 00:54:42.040
She is enormous.

00:54:42.040 --> 00:54:43.700
And she is proportionate,

00:54:43.700 --> 00:54:46.200
So she looks like you
have just taken someone

00:54:46.200 --> 00:54:48.780
and sized them up on
the Sims height scaler.

00:54:48.780 --> 00:54:49.870
Everything has gone.

00:54:49.870 --> 00:54:51.510
She's not a tall, thin person.

00:54:51.510 --> 00:54:52.444
And she's Irish.

00:54:52.444 --> 00:54:54.610
And she has one lazy eye,
that sort of wanders about

00:54:54.610 --> 00:54:56.314
and looks at other things.

00:54:56.314 --> 00:54:57.730
It's not actually
looking at them.

00:54:57.730 --> 00:55:00.170
But she'll tell you it is
because she's horrible person.

00:55:00.170 --> 00:55:01.794
And when she's having
a bad day, she'll

00:55:01.794 --> 00:55:03.240
get on the--
schlomp-- I need you

00:55:03.240 --> 00:55:05.550
to read me Veronica
Mars porn over Skype.

00:55:05.550 --> 00:55:06.610
I'm like, OK.

00:55:06.610 --> 00:55:07.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:07.110 --> 00:55:10.765
I can do-- you have come upon
a coping mechanism I can meet.

00:55:13.540 --> 00:55:16.770
It's like having your
very own evil leprechaun.

00:55:16.770 --> 00:55:18.560
And she is absolutely splendid.

00:55:18.560 --> 00:55:19.494
I love Sarah to death.

00:55:19.494 --> 00:55:21.410
And she's one of the
most bloody-minded people

00:55:21.410 --> 00:55:22.610
I know that is not me.

00:55:23.460 --> 00:55:24.460
We get along fabulously.

00:55:24.460 --> 00:55:25.793
She's one of my favorite humans.

00:55:25.793 --> 00:55:26.820
She's also a YA author.

00:55:26.820 --> 00:55:28.990
So she gets a lot
of crap for stuff

00:55:28.990 --> 00:55:32.470
that I get no crap for at
all, which frustrates us both.

00:55:32.470 --> 00:55:33.480
Not because I want crap.

00:55:33.480 --> 00:55:36.190
But because no one deserves
crap for things like,

00:55:36.190 --> 00:55:38.070
I freely admit that
I wrote fan fiction

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:40.035
because I'm trying to
be aspirational for all

00:55:40.035 --> 00:55:41.830
of the young women of the
world that might someday

00:55:41.830 --> 00:55:43.380
want to become
professional authors.

00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:48.860
I get people going, wow,
Mira Grant like fan fic.

00:55:48.860 --> 00:55:51.070
And she gets people
going, plagiaristic slut.

00:55:51.070 --> 00:55:54.110
And I'm like, how, wait-- no.

00:55:54.110 --> 00:55:54.810
Sarah, come on.

00:55:54.810 --> 00:55:56.640
We're going to leave now.

00:55:56.640 --> 00:55:57.950
And she actually joins in.

00:55:57.950 --> 00:56:00.120
When I say for science,
she'll be like yes.

00:56:00.120 --> 00:56:03.680
Let's eat all of these
pies for science.

00:56:03.680 --> 00:56:05.140
So we ate a lot of pie.

00:56:05.140 --> 00:56:06.770
And Sarah is splendid.

00:56:06.770 --> 00:56:08.592
If you like YA fiction
at all, or if you

00:56:08.592 --> 00:56:10.550
have someone in your life
who likes YA fiction,

00:56:10.550 --> 00:56:13.670
I really recommend her
Lynburn Legacy books,

00:56:13.670 --> 00:56:15.450
which are the story
of a girl named

00:56:15.450 --> 00:56:19.140
Cami and her imaginary
friend, who is not imaginary,

00:56:19.140 --> 00:56:21.340
but is very, very hot.

00:56:21.340 --> 00:56:23.450
And Sarah had written
the first of those

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:25.170
before we actually
became friends.

00:56:25.170 --> 00:56:28.580
Which is why I will give
her endless oceans of shit

00:56:28.580 --> 00:56:31.470
for the fact that there is
a rhyme about the Lynburns

00:56:31.470 --> 00:56:33.640
in the Lynburn Legacy
that does not scan.

00:56:36.600 --> 00:56:37.740
I'm like, no, no, honey.

00:56:37.740 --> 00:56:39.340
No, no, no, no.

00:56:39.340 --> 00:56:40.730
Your poetry has to scan.

00:56:40.730 --> 00:56:42.270
That's what poetry is for.

00:56:42.270 --> 00:56:45.930
Apple red, corn of gold,
and not everyone gets old.

00:56:45.930 --> 00:56:47.730
Like no, no.

00:56:47.730 --> 00:56:48.620
No, no.

00:56:48.620 --> 00:56:50.420
We can fix this.

00:56:50.420 --> 00:56:53.429
If you had just time traveled
six months into the future,

00:56:53.429 --> 00:56:55.220
it would have been like
we are friends now.

00:56:55.220 --> 00:56:56.990
I would have fixed it for you.

00:56:56.990 --> 00:56:59.410
So I get to fix these
things for her from now on.

00:56:59.410 --> 00:57:00.420
Sarah is splendid.

00:57:00.420 --> 00:57:02.550
Sarah is best.

00:57:02.550 --> 00:57:05.790
AUDIENCE: I know that
your oeuvre is broad.

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:10.480
But I want to ask you-- I
think of you most strongly

00:57:10.480 --> 00:57:12.185
in the Newsflesh--

00:57:12.185 --> 00:57:13.310
MIRA GRANT: Many people do.

00:57:13.310 --> 00:57:14.210
AUDIENCE: --trilogy.

00:57:14.210 --> 00:57:19.290
And I want to ask, of the
embarrassment of riches

00:57:19.290 --> 00:57:26.530
of zombie media and literature
available, what do you like?

00:57:26.530 --> 00:57:29.550
MIRA GRANT: Well, the problem
is in my reading tastes,

00:57:29.550 --> 00:57:31.440
I am just as dichotomist.

00:57:31.440 --> 00:57:35.200
Because I really love the
literary equivalent of the bad

00:57:35.200 --> 00:57:36.550
B horror .

00:57:36.550 --> 00:57:40.090
Like if you completely
commit to what you're doing,

00:57:40.090 --> 00:57:41.600
I am with you.

00:57:41.600 --> 00:57:44.590
I will follow you into
that dark, terrible place

00:57:44.590 --> 00:57:45.931
of terrible, dark darkness.

00:57:45.931 --> 00:57:48.430
But I'm like, oh, you're doing
something interesting and new

00:57:48.430 --> 00:57:49.660
and I've never seen this.

00:57:49.660 --> 00:57:52.080
Let's follow you into
the intellectual fields

00:57:52.080 --> 00:57:54.479
of halcyon flowers,
which is bad.

00:57:54.479 --> 00:57:56.520
I highly recommend the
"Raising of Stony Mayhall"

00:57:56.520 --> 00:58:00.150
by Daryl Gregory, which
is essentially the zombie

00:58:00.150 --> 00:58:00.689
Jesus book.

00:58:00.689 --> 00:58:01.980
And it's a beautifully written.

00:58:01.980 --> 00:58:05.380
It's absolutely ingenious.

00:58:05.380 --> 00:58:07.200
I do like Jonathan Mabery.

00:58:07.200 --> 00:58:08.910
He was a very, very sweet man.

00:58:08.910 --> 00:58:12.020
And he has his "Dead of
Night," "Fall of Night,"

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:14.630
x of Night books.

00:58:14.630 --> 00:58:17.290
Jonathan is a really nice
guy, who puts up with the fact

00:58:17.290 --> 00:58:19.216
that I know that his
virology is crap.

00:58:19.216 --> 00:58:21.840
And I give him crap for his crap
virology every time I see him.

00:58:21.840 --> 00:58:24.440
He's like yes, yes dear.

00:58:24.440 --> 00:58:25.810
Not all of us review.

00:58:25.810 --> 00:58:27.570
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:27.570 --> 00:58:29.752
I think that's meant
to be a compliment.

00:58:29.752 --> 00:58:31.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:31.110 --> 00:58:32.250
It's not.

00:58:32.250 --> 00:58:34.510
But we can take it.

00:58:34.510 --> 00:58:36.230
I hate mentioning
it in this context

00:58:36.230 --> 00:58:38.479
because it kind of gives
away some of what it's about.

00:58:38.479 --> 00:58:40.550
But the single best
book I read in 2014

00:58:40.550 --> 00:58:43.940
was the "Girl With All
the Gifts," by M.K. Carey.

00:58:43.940 --> 00:58:45.540
It is only out in
hardcover right now.

00:58:45.540 --> 00:58:46.960
Though it is also an ebook.

00:58:46.960 --> 00:58:48.500
If you see it in
a bookstore, it's

00:58:48.500 --> 00:58:51.240
a very yellow-orange cover,
with just the silhouette

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:53.050
of a girl like this, against it.

00:58:53.050 --> 00:58:54.310
And it's genius.

00:58:54.310 --> 00:58:55.850
It's so good.

00:58:55.850 --> 00:59:00.120
And I wish I wasn't telling
you as much about it

00:59:00.120 --> 00:59:02.860
as the context of the
statement tells you.

00:59:02.860 --> 00:59:04.360
But is so worth reading.

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:06.070
It is so worth your time.

00:59:06.070 --> 00:59:13.020
And it is a beautiful example of
how gender equality in science

00:59:13.020 --> 00:59:15.994
fiction doesn't have to
be a thing you work for.

00:59:15.994 --> 00:59:18.410
One of my favorite movies of
last five years was "Wreck-It

00:59:18.410 --> 00:59:21.000
Ralph," which, if you
look at "Wreck-It Ralph,"

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.500
they completely, effortlessly,
without any visible strain,

00:59:25.500 --> 00:59:28.980
any compromisation of the
story, any unnecessary romance,

00:59:28.980 --> 00:59:35.380
set up a thing where your
protagonist and your secondary

00:59:35.380 --> 00:59:37.580
protagonist, who I can't
pronounce right now--

00:59:37.580 --> 00:59:40.780
you have two men and two women.

00:59:40.780 --> 00:59:45.960
In the antagonist camp,
you have a man and a woman.

00:59:45.960 --> 00:59:47.554
And there's no effort.

00:59:47.554 --> 00:59:49.470
There's no point where
you feel like, oh, they

00:59:49.470 --> 00:59:51.630
made Taffyta a girl because
they wanted to have balance.

00:59:51.630 --> 00:59:52.130
No.

00:59:52.130 --> 00:59:54.080
They just made a
female character,

00:59:54.080 --> 00:59:55.660
who was an absolute bitch.

00:59:55.660 --> 00:59:56.650
And it's lovely.

00:59:56.650 --> 00:59:58.654
And it's beautifully done.

00:59:58.654 --> 01:00:00.070
And the "Girl With
All the Gifts,"

01:00:00.070 --> 01:00:01.465
manages a very similar balance.

01:00:01.465 --> 01:00:03.090
Where you're reading
through and going,

01:00:03.090 --> 01:00:04.880
there is no character
who is in here

01:00:04.880 --> 01:00:07.710
to be the dude, the
chick, the-- this.

01:00:07.710 --> 01:00:11.410
They are just people who are
stuck in this bad situation

01:00:11.410 --> 01:00:14.200
and trying to survive
this bad situation.

01:00:14.200 --> 01:00:16.440
And it's beautiful.

01:00:16.440 --> 01:00:17.950
This is absolutely lovely.

01:00:17.950 --> 01:00:20.600
And then David Wellington, who
did Monster Island trilogy--

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:22.349
he did "Monster Island,"
"Monster Nation,"

01:00:22.349 --> 01:00:25.480
"Monster World"-- has
a new book coming out.

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:28.150
Which I just blurbed for him
and I'm very excited about.

01:00:28.150 --> 01:00:34.320
And it is called--
I don't remember

01:00:34.320 --> 01:00:35.820
what it's called,
which is terrible.

01:00:35.820 --> 01:00:36.710
Because it has no cover.

01:00:36.710 --> 01:00:38.370
And the covers are
what I always remember.

01:00:38.370 --> 01:00:39.453
But it's David Wellington.

01:00:39.453 --> 01:00:41.650
And he is great.

01:00:41.650 --> 01:00:44.300
So I see people looking
at watches and such.

01:00:44.300 --> 01:00:45.800
So I assume you
have work to get to.

01:00:45.800 --> 01:00:48.250
Do we have any other questions
before I sign books and we

01:00:48.250 --> 01:00:50.650
all-- oh, yes, we have
one other question.

01:00:50.650 --> 01:00:55.520
AUDIENCE: So where did you
get the Mira Grant name from?

01:00:55.520 --> 01:00:57.980
MIRA GRANT: It's
kind of fun there.

01:00:57.980 --> 01:00:59.580
It is a combination of factors.

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:02.650
I wrote down every last
name I could come up

01:01:02.650 --> 01:01:06.310
with that had one or more
references to classic horror

01:01:06.310 --> 01:01:08.460
and science fiction movies.

01:01:08.460 --> 01:01:09.720
And it was purely movies.

01:01:09.720 --> 01:01:10.557
I stuck with those.

01:01:10.557 --> 01:01:12.390
And then I wrote out a
bunch of first names.

01:01:12.390 --> 01:01:13.561
And take them to my editor.

01:01:13.561 --> 01:01:15.060
Because my editor
had said he really

01:01:15.060 --> 01:01:16.935
wanted me to have a
pseudonym for these books

01:01:16.935 --> 01:01:18.780
for very valid reasons.

01:01:18.780 --> 01:01:20.840
And said I want to
be Samantha Grant.

01:01:20.840 --> 01:01:23.180
And he said, OK, the
dot.com is unavailable.

01:01:26.230 --> 01:01:30.910
Can we get the dot.com The
dot.com for Samantha Grant

01:01:30.910 --> 01:01:34.380
is being camped by a soccer mom,
who has not updated since 1994,

01:01:34.380 --> 01:01:37.590
and would not give
me her domain.

01:01:37.590 --> 01:01:40.620
I don't mind you having
the domain of your name.

01:01:40.620 --> 01:01:41.929
But maybe update it.

01:01:41.929 --> 01:01:43.720
And when you're coming
up with a pseudonym,

01:01:43.720 --> 01:01:45.780
it turns out that being
able to get the dot.com

01:01:45.780 --> 01:01:48.280
is a hugely important factor.

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:51.250
So we went down the first
name list and we hit on Mira.

